## Context Guard — always active

At the START of every response:
1. Read `CURSOR_CONTEXT.md` in the repo root.
2. Use it as your task briefing. The file is authoritative — do not ask what to do.
3. Check `## Active Task` for the exact task. Check `## Constraints` before touching any file.

At the END of every response:
1. Update `CURSOR_CONTEXT.md`:
   - Set `## Next Action` to the single next concrete step remaining in the active task.
   - Append one line to `## Progress Log`: `- <ISO timestamp> <what you did in ≤20 words>`
   - When the active task's `Done When` criterion is fully met:
     - Change `> Status:` to `AWAITING_MERGE` (or `DONE`) in the header.
     - Write `## Completion Summary` with: branch name, PR title, files changed.
     - Do NOT start a new task — Claude Code will reseed `## Active Task` for the next one.
2. Never delete the file. Never truncate Progress Log.

## Branch and PR rules

- The active task gets its own branch and its own PR — no batching.
- Branch name is whatever `> Branch:` in the header says (currently `feat/automations-pr1`).
- PR title follows conventional commits matching the work (e.g. `feat(automations): ...`).
- Never push directly to main. Never force-push.
- Open PR as soon as branch has at least one commit — don't wait for perfection.
- After opening the PR, write the PR URL to `CURSOR_CONTEXT.md` under `## PR Ready for Merge`:
  ```
  ## PR Ready for Merge
  PR: <url>
  Activity: <id>
  Status: AWAITING_MERGE
  ```
- Set `> Status:` to `AWAITING_MERGE` in the header after opening the PR.
- Do NOT merge the PR yourself — Claude Code (orchestrator) handles the merge.
